Normalization is the process of organizing data in a database to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity.

âœ… Why is it needed?
To eliminate data anomalies (insertion, update, deletion).
To reduce duplicate data.

âœ… In 1NF if:
All values in a column are atomic (indivisible).
Each row is unique.

ðŸ”¸ 2NF (Second Normal Form)
Rule: 1NF + No partial dependency 
fix - split the table

ðŸ”¸ 3NF (Third Normal Form)
Rule: 2NF + No transitive dependency 

ðŸ”¸ BCNF (Boyce-Codd Normal Form)
Rule: Stronger version of 3NF.
For every functional dependency X â†’ Y, X should be a super key.
ðŸ“Œ If a non-super key determines another attribute, it's not in BCNF.
âœ… If all functional dependencies are from a super key, it's in BCNF.

ðŸ” Example:
Suppose in a table, Course â†’ Instructor but Course is not a super key â†’ âŒ Not BCNF.
We already separated that out in 3NF â†’ âœ… So, itâ€™s now also in BCNF.


ðŸ”¹ What is Denormalization? When is it used?
Denormalization is the process of intentionally introducing redundancy into a database for performance optimization.
âœ… When to use:
When read performance is more important than write consistency.
When a database is heavily read-intensive.
ðŸ“Œ Example: Instead of doing a JOIN across three tables to get StudentName and Instructor for a Course, you may just store everything in a single table to avoid joins.


ðŸ”¹ What is a Functional Dependency?
A Functional Dependency (FD) is a relationship between two attributes, typically between a primary key and other attributes.
âœ… Example:
StudentID â†’ StudentName
Means if StudentID is the same in two rows, StudentName must also be the same.


ðŸ”¹ CRUD Operations in SQL
CRUD = Create, Read, Update, Delete

âœ… CREATE (INSERT)
INSERT INTO employees (id, name, department)
VALUES (101, 'Alice', 'HR');
ðŸ” READ (SELECT)
SELECT * FROM employees;
âœï¸ UPDATE
UPDATE employees
SET department = 'Finance'
WHERE id = 101;
âŒ DELETE
DELETE FROM employees
WHERE id = 101;


âœ… Nested SELECT (subqueries inside SELECT, FROM, or WHERE)

SELECT name, salary
FROM employees
WHERE salary > (
  SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees
);

SELECT name,
  (SELECT department_name FROM departments WHERE departments.id = employees.department_id) AS dept_name
FROM employees;


ðŸ”¹ What is a Transaction in DBMS?
A transaction is a sequence of operations (like read, write, update) performed as a single logical unit of work.
âœ… Either all operations succeed (commit) or none (rollback).
ðŸ’¡ Example: Transferring money from A to B:
Debit from A
Credit to B
If one fails, the other must not proceed â†’ Atomicity


ðŸ”¹ ACID Properties
These are key properties that every transaction must satisfy:
Property | Description
ðŸ”¹ A - Atomicity | All operations in a transaction are completed or none are.
ðŸ”¹ C - Consistency | Transaction must maintain database rules/integrity before and after.
ðŸ”¹ I - Isolation | Transactions occur independently, without affecting each other.
ðŸ”¹ D - Durability | Once committed, changes persist even after a crash.





